,Recommended,242760,30913250,Posted: 2 April,all,Adequate,"Given the amount of time I've pumped into this game since V.57 I figured it's time I gave it a decent review.Despite The Forest being an early access title it is vigorously worked on and polished out by the developers; they really haven't missed a beat when it comes to scheduled updates being pushed out. They listen to the community and although they haven't addressed every bug or flaw, they do seem to comprehend players' thoughts and concerns quite well. It's one of the few, if not the only EA title that I don't regret buying and playing.Let's start with the good:*PROS**Survival and staying alive. The first thing you'll probably notice upon your crash landing is that you're hungry and thirsty, which you'll easily see on your HUD. Drinking and eating doesn't feel like a chore like in other survival games, but it's most definitely important if you don't want to starve to death or die of thirst.Your stamina also depends on how healthy you are, whether you're tired or not, or whether you're hungry or thirsty. You'll find different ways to satisfy these needs, and once used to it it becomes sort-of second nature. Whether it being hunting or fishing, creating water collectors, eating available safe vegetation, boiling pond water or eating the spare snacks and food left over from the airplane, there is an abundance of ways to maintain your basic needs.*Extraordinary sandbox gameplay. If you're into building and creating just about any structure that comes across your imagination, you'll be delighted to know that a lot is possible with the building and construction mechanics as a whole. You'll probably start off small but if you give it the time to learn the basics (Watch youtube videos, trial and error, or learn from experienced builders), you'll likely eventually move on to massive defenses, structures, bases, buildings, etc etc.The developers often implement new features to the construction aspect of the game, and I haven't been disappointed by what's been implemented thus far. Building destruction can be toggled on or off depending on your preferences, I always kept it on to increase difficulty whilst defending a building location from enemies.Crafting items for your inventory is enjoyable once you're familiarized with the required material to create something with. A lot of it is basic common sense, but for creating something you're unaware of the specifications of, to put it simply, Google and The Forest wiki is your friend. From there all one needs to do is find said materials, craft the item, and you're good to go.*The Natives & Mutants. Depending on what you're comfortable with, you can chose to play a game with or without them (Peaceful mode). On single player they're probably going to scare the crap out of you, but that eventually passes; they will keep you on your toes though until you're used to it. Muiltiplayer brings a greater sense of ease from them, but the threat is always there. Fighting them off in greater numbers is always easier. There are a variety of weapons you can find within caves or you can craft yourself that will increase your chances for survival. You'll learn with time where or where to not set up a base depending on your tolerance for enemies coming along to destroy it and viciously attack you.The enemy AI overall is quite good, and you'll eventually learn they in fact have noticeable patterns that you can ultimately take advantage of. As time progresses and you defeat them more & more, you'll find that you will encounter harder cannibals and mutants to defeat. The choice to engage them is up to you whether you're the type to just run away or if you're the type to duke it out. There are a variety of traps and defenses you can construct to be utilized for your advantage and overall safety.*The atmosphere and Environment. Overall it's quite beautiful. The Forest literally feels alive with different types of wildlife ranging from birds and ducks to deer, squirrels, rabbits and more. Reptilian life is also present. The wind in-game is the most realistic out of any game I've ever played. There is a lot of attention to detail whether it be towards wildlife or vegetation in general. The water looks gorgeous whether it be lakes and ponds or of course the ocean. Towards the northern most region of the peninsula there is even a snow/cold weather themed section that will truly put your survival skills to the test.The caves ingame are as extraordinary as they are realistic. The ambience and overall feeling you have when entering them for the first time is quite different than anything I've experienced gaming in a while.  The sounds experienced, especially the echoing of enemies and general sounds proves to be a memorable experience. The entire network of caves can prove challenging and foreboding for new players, but once you get the basics down such as creating a light source it isn't all-too bad. Bad guys in such locations such as mutants and the cannibals can provide one with a jump scare or two; although once dealt with the danger factor degrades, except from things like falling a great distance downwards, etc.*The CONS**Modders and hackers, trolls and griefers. If you're playing multiplayer and aren't playing with a group of friends on a private server, you're almost certainly going to encounter them. Saving often is a must if the latter, especially if you're running a server. This isn't an issue in single player, or if building destruction is turned off, but there are numerous ways these individuals can detract from fun whether it be spawning in all weapons to PVP you, spawning in 500 logs to crash the server, etc. I'm aware that some individuals utilize mods as a way of playing the game, but in my opinion it detracts from the fun and overall point of engaging gameplay.*Bugs and crashes. Depending on whether you're hosting a server or not (Listen server, I have no knowledge with dedicated) these can be numerous and frustrating. They can be small, like wildlife or cannibals running around in circles forever, or they can be detracting, such as the game crashing, objects and world disappearing, getting stuck on a rope, etc. The developers are constantly working on these matters though, but regardless I'd again advise to save as often as possible just in-case.Thus sums up the PROS and CONS that I can think of off the top of my head.In conclusion I'd overall HIGHLY recommend this game to anyone who likes the survival genre, anyone who likes the ability to craft and construct numerous items & structures, anyone who likes awesome melee combat against savages and horrendous mutants, and anyone who enjoys exploration in a game as a whole and defending what they've created against a potential onslaught of enemies."
