,Recommended,242760,34665898,Posted: 1 September,all,Riddlewrong,"The Forest is a fun exploration/survival game with an interesting story and great progression -- just don't overstay your welcome.The survival elements are great: You need to eat, drink, and sleep in order to have the energy to perform tasks like cutting down trees, building a settlement, hunting, gathering, running from cannibals, etc. Everything is interconnected in such a way that it truly feels like there is a survival economy that needs to be respected and maintained.The cannibals are scary, and more importantly, they are potentially very dangerous. There is a bit of a hiccup, though. The aggression of the cannibals is linked to a few different factors. The most obvious one is that if you attack them and some of them escape, the tribe will become aware of you as a threat and start sending out heavier patrols. The more conflict you have with them, the worse it gets. In addition, if you have an impact on the environment such as cutting down trees, this will also raise aggression. Lastly, if you explore the caves and progress the story, the aggression will yet again rise.It's really fun to run into new cannibal types and even mutants, but if you're not careful, it can get WAY out of control. No matter how strong your defenses are, at max aggression the conflict you have with the cannibals is an all outwarthat you can never truly win because cannibal spawns are infinite. There are a number of traps in the game, but you can't really make effective use of them outside of wooded areas. If you build a base on the beach or in a clearing, for example, your traps will be almost useless. Cannibalsavoidtraps unless they blend in with the environment at least somewhat. Most traps are made out of logs, so it makes sense that they're triggered much more often when you set them near trees. If you just put a trap on the ground out in the open, they'll run around it 100% of the time. They're clever like that. Also, they dodge a lot in melee and get behind you. Like, way more than you might expect. Fighting them takes practice. Very nimble, those cannibals.Regardless, at high aggression levels, the cannibals will eventually launch constant attacks on your base with large numbers of fairly strong cannibals and mutants, even in broad daylight. At that point, they'll even attack your base when you're not there! Meanwhile, you don't really get any weaponry to deal with large scale assaults like that. You'll be forced to take potshots at them with a bow from your towers (which can quickly be knocked down by a mutant, might I add) or lob molotovs and kite while you slash at things who get too close to you. It's not impossible to fend them off, but it becomes a serious chore, especially if you're solo.The point is, if you play the game as a survival sim and don't try to actually finish the story, you will get to a point where exploring the island is a huge hassle because the patrols and enemy strength eventually become ridiculous. This is what I meant by overstaying your welcome.If you want to get the most enjoyment out of this game as a solo player or duo, I suggest keeping it simple and building a few tiny hunting camps around the peninsula. The small raft is probably one of the most useful things you can build, especially if you have camps near water. Avoid fighting cannibals on the surface, and concentrate on exploring the landscape. The less aggressive you get with them, the easier it'll be to get things done. Find the caves, go down into them, get scared senseless, and search thoroughly. 90% of the game's story and progression is a result of exploring the caves for clues and unique items needed to continue to areas you couldn't reach before."
76561198074671324,Recommended,242760,17141659,"Posted: 20 July, 2015",all,King Arthur,>Start the game and decide to set up on the beach>Decide to build a bonfire>Mutants attack my camp anyway>Start a bodypile next to bonfire>Seagulls really enjoy decomposing corpses>They all start flying into the bonfire>I now have an unlimited supply of feathers and arrows cause of my ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥♥ seagull trap10/10 would accidentally mass murder seagulls again
,Recommended,242760,18348000,"Posted: 5 October, 2015",all,Green Life Saver,"For a while this game was incredibly buggy; to the point of being unplayable. To some, it may still seem this way. However, if you look at it more objectively you see that most of it isn't buggy. The only two awful bugs that they absolutely NEED to fix to make this game work is the fact that there are some world holes around ponds, and that sometimes you fall down ropes (NOTE: The rope glitch has been fixed). Otherwhise, the AI, the combat, the crafting, everything other than those two things, works marvelously. The only thing that The Forest is currently lacking in is bug fixing, and content. Two things which it SHOULD be lacking in, at this point in the game.Also the Developers are ♥♥♥♥ing great.But anyway, onto the reasons I love the game itself.The thing that really stood out to me wasn't the pretty graphics, or the creepy cannibals, or the survival aspect, it was the cannibal's AI. There are SO many things that the cannibals react and adapt to. I'll give a few examples1: The Cannibals can be somewhat reasoned with - The first few times you see the cannibals, especially if you are NEAR the plane (they see you as less hostile the closer to the plane you are) they aren't there to kill you, or even hurt you. They come to check you out, see if you're a threat, and they'll probably just leave you alone if you're not too much of a threat. For instance, as long as you make sure they are in your line of sight, you don't back up to their advances, or go towards them threateningly, they won't attack. If they run to you and attack once, block it, and then if they attack again, they will ACTUALLY mean to fight. Sometimes they just want to see if they can land a hit, and will back off after you block it. Cutting down trees, overhunting, and overbuilding also makes them more hostile. Hiding your fires from view makes them less hostile as well, as they hate fire. There are many other things that make them more/less hostile, but I myself don't know many anyway. The last, most noteable thing is that if you overhunt, and do things to bother the cannibals, and if you let survivors that spot you get away, they will send raiding parties of increasing numbers after you, until they finally get tired of you surviving them, and send the creepy, huge monsters that are in the trailer at you2: The Combat Is Realistic, and the AI isn't bad at all, especially for an Alpha game - The Forest's combat, while a bit wonky (especially with player versus player) looks fine from first person; it seems heavy hitting, and brutal, with each of your hits knocking the cannibals back, occasionally knocking teeth out. And while the blocking system is currently a bit over powered (you literally can just hold the block button and take 0 damage from hits, provided you have the stamina), they are fixing it slowly; it can't be easy to make a game balanced. The AI acts exactly how you'd expect feral, animal like cannibals to strike at you. They run at you, hit once or twice, then back off because they're frightened of you. (Note this is for the ones that look like little Gollums.)3: The Variety of Cannibals - This one is a bit of a list, but these tribes compete, and often fight. This also includes the fact that there are a finite number of cannibals in the Forest; they run out eventually.1 Starvers: These are the gollum lookin' dudes I was talking about. They are feral, creepy, and like to laugh maniacally. They are also weak, quick, and probably one of the easiest enemies in the game2 The White Cannibals?: Not sure what their real name is, but they are white skinned to the point of being pale as hell, they are one of the more civilised cannibal tribes, and will do the aforementioned out-checking of you (they're less hostile than the Starvers) They kinda look like aliens sometimes.3 The Brown Cannibals?: Also not sure; these look like normal humans, entirely, they are also more peaceful, and are fairly strong, along with the White Cannibals.4 The Mutants: Ok here's where we get creepy; these are the huge, multi-limbed animals that like to smash your defenses, and are incredibly difficult to kill. You need fire to kill these bad boys. They come in two categories: The Virginia (Aka spider mutants, they have many legs and are quick, blind, and creepy as hell) and the Octopus Mutants: Which have many many arms, and are strong and chargy.5 Not sure if these deserve their own category, but they are incredibly creepy and sometimes kinda deadly: Mutant Babies. They are deformed monsters that jump at you, and make creepy noises. They are in caves solely.I might edit this to put in more cons as I see them, but for now the only real thing that they need to fix is the two world breaking bugs, the blocking system, and adding some more content as well as making boats actually viable. This game is great, but you might want to wait until it comes out."
