,Recommended,242760,10921729,"Posted: 28 June, 2014",all,hoyholyhoy,"People seem to forget that games like this are in ealry alpha phase, and continue to write them off due to bugs and other anomalies that can and WILL be fixed in the near future. Instead, people like to focus on the things the game doesn't have (which can be healthy to a degree when trying to help the development of a game) but it's taken so far and they expect so much out of something so barely out of its conception stage that it really rubs me the wrong way when people like that are somehow influencing others into not deciding for themselves whether or not to experience the game on their own. That being said, I to a look at what this game DOES offer, and let me tell you: I freaking love it.Here's the thing, I really don't like playing survival games. I usually turn my head and shrug whenever I see another game in this genre pumped out, but something about this game cought me. Some sense of an atmosphere I hadn't seen in a survival game.  I think one key thing that engrossed me into this dark and sh-t-my-pants game was that you are all alone. There is nobody there to fend for you, help protect or look out for you but yourself. This also worked in my favor as my past experiences with literally every other survival game have ended not by the cruel, demanding world around me, but by other uncooperative players trolling along my path only hindering my experience with the game. With The Forest, I find a sense of serene horror, in the likes of Blair Witch Project. It's as if the quiet stillness around me paralyzes me with anxiety, seeing that mob of cannibals charge me from a distance feels more real than I've ever experienced in a game. Something in this game's nature just does it differently for me. There are no zombies or senseless goons to have you snarking at the lack of realism like in other games, only psychotically intelligent cannibals. and some of the freakiest mutant test subject looking sub-humans that look straight out of The Human Centipede I've ever seen. All this combined with fantastic visuals and especially well thought out lighting make this game something special.Overall, the game clearly has issues that need to be sorted out (as would any game in early alpha phase) but some of the features I hear they will be implementing only make me more hungry to play. Apparenly we will see a co-op mode which is one feature alone that would sell me again, being my favorite aspect of any game (ex. L4D, Resident Evil or Evolve.)I would focus on things this game doesn't have if I didn't already thoroughly enjoy it even with it's sometimes humorous flaws.For a game this promising, in such an early stage of development, for only $15, I wouldn't pass it up, especially if you're looking for A. A morbidly terrifying experience B. A great, easy to understand and learn survival ""siimulator?"" C. A fun walk in the forest to grandma's.8/10 from me [so far].List of bugs I've encountered so far:*When loading a save, my inventory becomes empty, once I equip the airplane axe, I start walking below the ground and die.*When low on lung capacity, if I swing the axe at a tree, it will double swing but only one will detect a hit.*Only once has it happened, but for around 10 minutes I was unable to swing or block with the axe entirely.*When crafting, if I select booze, it cannot be removed from the crafting area unless I craft a molotov*Only once has it happened, but when fighting one of the cannibals, they froze, then once I hit them, they exploded with the their feet still attached to the ground likehttps://www.youtube.com/watch?v=klVhwlwHhY4"
