76561198022764844,Recommended,242760,12106102,"Posted: 15 September, 2014",all,Ser Arthur Dayne,"The Short Version: Wait for the beta or the official launch.  None of the features are implemented in any kind of finished state.  It's better to spend money on a finished product, today, than to buy an unfinished/undesigned product for ""tomorrow"".  In all seriousness, this project might not even fully finish. (See TOWNS)I'm here to counter all these positive reviews by people who barely played 10 hours.Pros:This game has many outstanding concepts and features:>FPShooter non-shooterI've been waiting for games like these since TRIBES tRPG>Open-World>CraftingWeapons and supplies>ConstructionShelter and defenses>EnemiesDanger and tension from the native mutants>Needs drivenThe one game that doesn't need a hunger and rest and cold mod!>Dynamic WeatherDay to Night, Rainy/Sunny, possible snowy/frigid environment on the mountain.>Absence of storyIn a survival-game the ending is death and the story is literally the sum of the events of your game. There is no convoluted story to understand and follow. There is no main-line objective obstructing your progress.  It's more open-ended than anything out so far.  It's more solitary than any horror story.  You truly are alone and you truly don't know what to do next, rather than constantly hearing some tutorial or figuring out some menial puzzle, respectively.  This aspect of games are largely forgotten and gamers constantly feel like they got strangers holding their hands every time they play a new game.  It's refreshing to have a manual and a start game and to be set loose on this island without having to look at a picture of a slow-talking and historically-inaccurate representation of a person telling me how to wipe my own♥♥♥♥♥♥That is the best aspect of the game, though; it's list of features.Cons:And with that said, I move on to the finer points of the review.  Finer in terms of scope.  A more in-depth look at each point.  A more realistic gauge on what the game is, and where it lands on the scale between buy now and buy later.  Indeed, you wouldn't want a nice looking game that doesn't play well.None of the features are anywhere close to being implemented.  Yes, you can fish, and farm, and build a boat, and build a house, and chop down a tree, and so on.... you could do all these things and be satisfied for a few days just working your way through the list of features, but you won't find yourself doing any of them a second or third time.Very quickly, you learn that the quality of the implemented features are barely placeholder status.  Most things you can do are written off as an alpha feature when you read the responses to the complaint about it.  If you've ever played a hugely unsatisfying game then you'll know what I'm talking about. Chop down your twentieth tree and it's likely to be your last....out of boredom.  If there's a mutant attacking you he causes the game to play a spooky noise, which is quite thrilling.  The novelty of such things, however, wear out fast and soon even encountering the main threat of the game is like encountering a group of pidgeons being fed; utterly mundane.  That novelty would have hit me much better and would still be a factor if the game was immersive.  Sadly my experiences with these alpha features have likely ruined any future experience I might have with those features entirely.My review would likely be far more positive if the game had improved over time but the features keep getting added in a very unsatisfying way, and much too little in between too long times.  I have tried every build since v0.01 and it still feels like im playing the same game except with more annoyances.  Every time Space Engineers updates they have a game changing edition in a pretty well polished form.   So far, the form in which features are implemented with this game falls just short of ""worth throwing a tantrum"".I didn't even bother trying v0.06B.  Why are they populating the world when there's absolutely nothing for them to do?  These mutants can barely even do a patrol, let alone more complex scripting and even combat.  I'd rather they flush out the map borders, seeing as we can't even access the whole map yet.Features:>FPSCombat ranges from Clunky to downright garbage.  You can't even aim the bow properly and arrows collide with just about everything except your intended target.  Don't even get me started on melee.>Open-WorldWe can't even access the whole map.  The part of the map that we can access has very little to see and even less to do.  Once you realize you've finished building your base you lose all purpose and start going on suicide missions to lure out and kill a super mutant as a quasi-achievement.>CraftingJust like most other games, gather the materials and combine them.  Unlike most other games, theres VERY little to make.>BuildingProbably the feature that's gotten the most attention and the feature that's the least satisfying.  From stairs to walls to prefab-buildings, they all have some kind of kink in them when they're actually built.  Building them raises many more problems, and gathering the materials raises even more.  From crude mechanics like how trees are chopped, to fun-sapping useless mechanics like how trees fall over in perfectly lengthened logs, to broken mechanics like resource spawns (Rocks, farms, etc)>EnemiesRidiculous combat and encounter AI will have you annoyed not long before the terror wears thin.  From idiotic women following you around to waking up to a group of mask wearing dudes who like theyre guarding a basketball hoop...all of your interactions get old very fast and the AI shows it's intelligence quickly.  They'll dart in and retreat over and over to no effect.  They'll trigger the spooky mutant noise while perched in a tree, obviously stuck from a bug.   You'll walk into ghost-town camps.  You'll come across patrols making bee-lines between the water and some point outside of their nearest village.>Needs drivenFor a game that revolves around satisfying your needs, AKA SURVIVAL, it does really poorly in giving you options to solve your needs-related problems.  There's only one building in which you can rest, currently.  There's only one reliable food-source (forage) in a game where farming and breeding would be a no-brainer second and third option and should be their top priorities.  Cooking raw meat can break your fire and force you to build another fire and cook another piece of meat.  The main hunting technique, in a survival game, is to run up to it and hit it with an axe, whatever ""it"" is.  Wet/Dry and rest/energy is rudimentary at best and broken at other times.  The only real penalty is having an annoying tooltip remind you of how cold you are, or not being able to sprint.>Dynamic WeatherJust plain broken.  Thunderstorms frequency is way too high.  Night seems way longer, as if it's winter, and keeping yourself awake in day hours seems to be a trial in itself.  GTA III did it better a decade ago.>Absence of storyThough I wrote up on how good it is that this game has no real story, the evidence of the child in the beginning cutscene seems to suggest that a story isn't out of the picture.  It could just be that the absence of story is another alpha feature.In my opinion, you're better off waiting for a finished game or at least a BETA.  The way it is now, spending money is just spoiling a good finished game for you.  It's like buying the episode spoilers for your favorite show.  Don't reward complacency.  Buy the game when the devs actually develop the game further.  I've been sitting on this product in the same state for months."
